The real differentiation here is the world layer - the economy, social dynamics, and civilization evolution - not the agent capabilities themselves

Building an agent framework from scratch wastes months on tool use, error handling, and memory management when those are solved problems. The smarter move is leveraging existing agent frameworks to get the "hands" working immediately, then focusing all energy on what actually makes this project unique: designing the world and systems that agents interact with.
The recommendation is straightforward: wrap lightweight LLM API calls with basic tool access (browser, terminal, file system) for each citizen, then build the economic and social systems on top. Don't reinvent the agent wheel, but also don't need a heavyweight framework - just enough scaffolding to let citizens take actions in the world you're building. The agent itself is just a thin wrapper around LLM API calls with function calling—maybe a hundred lines of code per citizen. The real complexity and value is in building the world layer where these agents operate.Show moreDone这个问题我有明确的看法。
你的项目的独特价值是世界——经济、社会、文明演变的那一层。不是agent本身的能力。能上网、能写代码、能搜索——这些是commodity，现在所有人都在做这个，Claude Code、OpenHands、AutoGPT、各种开源agent框架全在卷这一层。
所以别在agent能力层上花时间。
用最简单的方式给每个居民一个"身体"就行：
python# 一个居民的"身体"就是：LLM + 几个工具函数
tools = [
    web_search,      # 搜索
    web_browse,      # 读网页
    write_file,      # 写文件
    run_code,        # 跑代码
    post_content,    # 发内容到外部平台
    plaza_speak,     # 在广场发言
    trade,           # 和其他居民交易
]

# 每个居民每轮就是一次LLM调用
response = llm_call(
    system=citizen.personality + citizen.goals,
    context=world_state,
    tools=tools
)
这不需要任何框架。就是API调用加function calling，你一个下午就能写完。
你真正要花心思写的是世界层：

